Data Preprocessing and MLTP Background Info

This dataset spans the past five seasons (S20-S24) of MLTP (Major League TagPro), the most elite competitive TagPro league in North America. I gathered data from each season from https://www.tagproleague.com/MLTP/stats, cleaned and filtered the data, appended the season number to each observation, and then joined the transformed data into one master dataset. I also created two smaller datasets from the master one, a dataset with just defenders and another with just offenders.

TagPro is a capture the flag (CTF) web browser game played between two teams of four players each on a variety of tile-based maps. Each person plays as a two-dimensional, paint-filled ball traversing the game with up/down/left/right keypresses as input. In competitive play, teams consist of two offenders and two defenders. The central objective is to grab the opponent's flag and carry it back without getting tagged with the imposition that teams may only capture if their flag is safe.

Offenders focus their efforts on grabbing the flag, holding the flag, staying alive until an opportunity arises, and then pushing into their own base to attempt to get a capture. Other duties include helping their defense tag or contain the enemy flag carrier, fighting for powerups, blocking adversaries to assist their teammates, and getting regrab. Regrab refers to the strategy of having one offender wait in the opponent's base when their partner already has the opponent's flag. If the offensive partner is popped, the other offender will instantly grab the flag when it teleports back to the opponent's base.

Defenders will focus primarily on keeping the flag secure. When the flag is grabbed, the defenders are responsible for chasing the flag carrier and tagging him. When flag carriers are tagged, they pop, and the flag is teleported back to its home tile in the base. Other duties for defenders include fighting for powerups, blocking for their flag carrier, and playing anti-re. Anti-re, short for anti-regrab, is a strategy developed to counter regrab involving a player guarding the empty flag tile in their own base. The point of this maneuver is that once the enemy flag carrier dies and the flag teleports back, there is a player to defend the flag from the other team's regrab.

With a basic understanding of the fundamentals of Tagpro, we can start to answer questions that would be important to certain groups of individuals within the community.


Questions of Interest

Competitive teams looking to scout players to draft for the next season want to know: Which players are performing very well in key metrics? For defenders, prevent, tags, powerups, and pop/tag ratio are some of the most heralded categories; for offenders, grabs, hold, scoring percentage, powerups, and caps are often considered the most important. Focusing on which players are dominating these areas should give some insight into who the best players are, which can be checked by conducting semi-structured interviews with experts in the field to weigh in with their thoughts on the important metrics and best players.

Players looking to step up their own gameplay or managers trying to improve their teams want to know: Which metrics are correlated most strongly with success? Which skills are the most important for a player to improve upon if they want to increase their level of success in-game? Team success is typically measured using either win/loss/tie record or by capture differential (Own captures - opponent captures). Capture differential is the logical choice, as we need some way to measure success quantitatively and precisely; W/L/T record is quantitative but less precise, since winning/losing by 1 is treated the same as winning/losing by 20. For statistics that accrue over time, the values must be transformed to per-minute statistics since players have different amounts of playtime; fractional statistics do not require preprocessing. I elected to define a variable called success_rate as the capture differential per minute for each individual player to then try to visualize the effects that each of the other variables have on my defined metric. This metric might need improvement if the expert panel disagrees with the implementation or it is unable to answer the posed research questions.


Important Terminology

  • Success rate: (Caps - Caps Against) / Minutes
  • pupm: Powerups per minute
  • cpm: Caps per minute
  • hpm: Hold per minute
  • gpm: Grabs per minute
  • tpm: Tags per minute
  • ppm: Prevent per minute
  • kdr: Kills / Deaths
  • poppm: Pops per minute
  • inbasepm: In-base returns per minute
  • quickpm: Quick returns per minute
  • savepm: Saves per minute

The above visualization utilizes scatterplots with the major offense stat catergories as predictors and the success rate as the response for each. A scatterplot is an excellent choice in this situation because not only does it offer an immediately salient representation of the linear correlation between the response and each predictor, but it also allows each individual data point to be examined (some type of aggregation or distrubtion would mask the individual points and only show a big picture view). Color and shape are jointly used to group the observations by season to increase the ease of interpretability under the gestalt law of similarity. The four scatterplots are additionally linked by an interactive rectangular brush; highlighting a section of points on any particular graph will gray out the rest of that graph as well as display in color only the data points on the other graphs that correspond to the highlighted points on the original graph. This allows for insights to be generated from patterns or trends between the scatterplots, as well as giving the capability to find an observation's corresponding point on all scatterplots instantly, without having to manually comb through the visual space three separate times. The same visualization technique is applied below to four of the defensive stat categories as well to give a broad overview of each position.

One potential downside of the above visualization is that while it does allow linking comparison and salient access to outliers across all seasons, it is difficult to see one season at a time. To make it easier to compare intraseasonal player performances, I created another visualization with even more information density and interactivity. Again, I used tooltip to display observation specific data on hover and color plus shape to indicate season, but also incorporated size to indicate success rate, which freed up the y axis for another metric. This way two of the top metrics could be compared in the same visual space without losing the success rate information. Another crucial addition is that the legend is now interactive, so the data can be selectively filtered by a user to display a single season at a time or view all five seasons at once. In the below visualization, by selecting S20 in the legend and examining the defense scatterplot, it is evident that the player called 'PingPrisoner' performed the best in both Tags Per Minute and Prevent Per Minute, suggesting he had the strongest defensive performance that season. However, without the ability to separate by season it is diffult to see the disparity between PingPrisoner and the rest of the defenders from S20; the pertinent observations in the visual space are occluded by the observations from the other seasons so it is important to have an additional filtering layer in the legend.

To make the top performers in each category even more salient, we can select only the top players from each of the statistical categories over a certain threshold value and display them neatly in a barplot. Again, the observations are partitioned by season using color, because it's important to know how strong a performance was both interseasonally and intraseasonally. The performances have also been sorted in decreasing order to minimize the temporal distance between preattentive processing and insight. Prevent per Minute, Tags per Minute, and Powerups per Minute top performeres are exhibited for defense key categories and Caps per Minute, Hold per Minute, and Grabs per Minute are similarly represented for offense.

Circling back to the second main question posed in the introduction, we would like to know which metrics correlate most strongly with success rate. A simple way to begin analytically computing the relationships between the variables would be to calculate the coefficient of determination ($R^2$) for each pairing of variables. However, the numerical strength of the linear relationship does not tell much about the shape of the distribution and in fact can be very misleading if there is a nonlinear relationship present. $R^2$ values can even be close to 1.0 despite the data being non-linear by nature, so having some manner in which to pictorially examine the relationships between variables adds a deeper understanding of the data and increases information density without losing the ability to see the strength of the linear correlation. By using a type of visual called a "scatter matrix", we can simultaneous generate many pairwise scatterplots and then scan the spatial envelope for patterns between the pairs and easily discount plots where the data appears to be randomly scattered in a point cloud.


Defense Pairwise Relationships

defense_success = alt.Chart(data_D).mark_circle().encode(
    alt.X(alt.repeat("column"), type='quantitative'),
    alt.Y(alt.repeat("row"), type='quantitative'),
    color="season",
    opacity=alt.condition(selection, alt.value(1), alt.value(0.2)),
    tooltip = ['player', 'season']
).properties(
    width=250,
    height=250
).repeat(
    row=['ppm', 'tpm', 'kdr', 'pupm', 'poppm', 'inbasepm', 'quickpm', 'savepm'],
    column=['success_rate', 'ppm', 'tpm']
).add_selection(
    selection
).interactive()

defense_success
Out[52]:

Interestingly, none of the defensive categories seem to have a positive or negative correlation with success rate. Every single pairwise scatterplot shows a cloud of seemingly random points, indicating that while the defensive metrics may capture how well an individual is performing, the individual's statistical performance has little bearing on the success of his team. While there were a handful of minor categories that were correlated with the other major categories (TPM and PPM), none of the minor categories nor TPM & PPM were correlated with success rate, so the current metrics are failing to capture what makes defenders succeed or fail.

For offense, the only statistic that seemed to have a strong correlation with success rate was caps per minute (and scoring percentage, which is multicollinear with caps per minute and not shown directly on the scatter matrix). Unfortunately, this makes it difficult to differentiate between great, decent, and horrible offenders if the only noticeable statistical difference is how likely they are to cap given that they have grabbed. Decison making and the ability to see and create opportunities and subsequently capitalize on them after a grab occurs are probably the most relevant factors to actually converting to a capture. Entirely new metrics may need to be derived to accurately capture the essence of this idea.

Visualization Evaluation Plan

  • Target question: Can participants figure out which metrics and players reign supreme?
  • Recruit: Mix of expert players and regular people with no knowledge of the game
  • Measures: Correlation coefficient for determining different stat categories compared to key stat metrics to see which categories indicate which teams perform the best
  • Approach: systematic surveys and semistructured interviews on experts to gather knowledge on their beliefs on the best players and metrics. Journaling with experts and regular users to get reactions and belief after interacting with the visualization
  • Instantiate: Experts will be asked for their a priori beliefs and then partake in the journaling while interacting with the visualizations. Regular users will have no a priori beliefs about such a niche topic and will go straight into the interaction stage.
  • Success criteria: To measure the accuracy, the expert belief responses will be compared to the visualization conclusions. To measure the efficacy, the regular user post-interaction responses will be measured against the ideas that the visualization was intended to convey


Evaluation Results

Evaluation was performed with one current professional player that participated in all of the seasons examined, one retired professional player and manager (now a data scientist!) that did not play in any of the seasons examined, and a regular person (data science masters student) familiar with videogames featuring capture the flag but no prior knowledge of TagPro or MLTP. This eclectic sampling allows for a breadth of insight from different backgrounds and experiences. The interaction capabilities of the charts went over quite well with all of the participants in terms of both engagement and ability for participants to pick out the top performers from each season. One qualm about the barplots was the lack of visual consistency, as some plots showed only a couple top performers and others showed more. A future iteration would probably have either a consistent number of top performers for every single category, or an implementation of a slider bar to dynamically change the number of top performances shown. In terms of being able to tell which categories were the most strongly correlated with success, participants struggled slightly more with the scatter matrix. While the amount of information is high, the important relationships were not as salient as they should have been for a good visualization. In hindsight, a scatter matrix is a much better tool for exploratory purposes than it is for succinctly conveying a message to an audience. Using the scatter matrix to investigate and then making a more information dense graph based on the findings with clutter removed would have a higher efficacy. Another note from the participant with no prior MLTP knowledge was that some of the metrics and their abbreviations were confusing, so I added a section at the beginning as a reference for what the abbreviations stand for. However, some of the meanings of the terminology even after knowing the abbreviation could be foreign to users outside of the set of people who have ever played capture the flag in a videogame. For the target audience of the visualization, this would not be problematic but a future iteration would probably exapand the definitions of the terms to be inclusive to any user who wanted to consume the content.
